ce:section.ce:para:
The interfacial tension of the oil-brine system was also studied elaborately as a function of CND concentration and surfactant type and concentration at 298.15 K and 14.7 psig (Table 4
                        ). It is observed in Table 4 that an increase of CND from 0 to 1000 ppm in seawater contributes to about a 15 % drop in the IFT. This can be attributed to the carbon nanodots arrangement at the oil-water interface. Typically, nanodots are soluble in the aqueous phase due to its hydrophilic nature. In the case of an oil/water system, nanodots are also “drawn” (with more attraction or less repulsion) to the interface through the electrostatic interaction between its own polar/acid/amide moieties and the polar moieties/heteroatoms of the crude oil. From Table 5
                        , the difference between the oil and water ζ-potential, |ζo - ζw|, increases slightly with the addition of the CND from 4.8 mV to 7.35 mV, indicating lesser repulsion between oil and CND. (The ζ-potential study is detailed further in the following section.) The addition of nanodots reduces the cohesive (intermolecular) force of oil/water by enhancing the adhesive nature of the interface, thereby increasing its surface energy and reducing the interfacial tension.
